This paper is likely to belong to the sub-category of cs.LG (Machine Learning) as it deals with training neural networks with binary weights and activations. It also involves stochastic gradient descent, which is a common optimization technique used in machine learning. 

It could also belong to cs.NE (Neural and Evolutionary Computing) as it deals with neural networks and their architecture. 

The paper also mentions intermediate representations and dot products, which are commonly used in computer vision (cs.CV) and artificial intelligence (cs.AI) research. 

Finally, the paper mentions the possibility of generalizing binary neural networks to other architectures such as recurrent neural networks, which could fall under the sub-category of cs.SY (Systems and Control).
